Different concentrations of TNT at WP6-N-GQDs/GCE were investigated by using DPV under optimal accumulation conditions, as illustrated in Fig. 4C. The reduction peak current gradually increased with the increasing of TNT concentrations. We chose the cathodic peak at −0.40V, which exhibited a linear response to the TNT concentration, for our assay signal. The corresponding calibration curve is shown in Fig. 4D. The reduction currents were proportional to the TNT concentration between 0.001μM and 1.0μM and between 1.0μM and 20.0μM with a detection limit of 0.95nM (S/N=3). The detection limit (LOD) was calculated according to the equation LOD=3S/b, where S is the standard deviation of the blank solution, b is the slope of the analytical curve. The regression equations are J (μAcm−1)=1.740C (μM) + 40.00 and J (μAcm−1)=33.20C (μM) + 13.65 with correlation coefficients of 0.996 and 0.966. The detection limit of 0.95nM is very low for detection of TNT in drinking water; since the maximum TNT concentration allowed by the U.S. Environmental Protection Agency in drinking water is 2ppb (1 ppb≈4.4nM) [56]. Moreover, we also compared the sensing performance of the WP6-N-CQD composites with those of other electrochemical sensing materials. As shown in Table 1
                        , the as-prepared WP6-N-CQD composite exhibited a higher detection performance than previously reported electrode materials. These results suggest that the WP6-N-CQD nanocomposites are promising nanomaterials for the enhanced electrochemical detection of TNT. The outstanding sensing performance could be related to the high electrocatalytic activity of N-CQDs and the excellent supramolecular recognition capability of WP6 (Table 2
                        ).
